DATABASE_URL="postgresql://USER:PASSWORD@localhost:5432/ai_reception_saas?schema=public"
NEXT_PUBLIC_APP_URL="http://localhost:3000"

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Auth context configuration (A-R2 dev-bypass deployment guard)
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# A "real-data environment" is any place real customer data can exist:
#   - NODE_ENV=production (a production runtime, e.g. `next start`), OR
#   - VERCEL_ENV is "production" or "preview" (a deployed Vercel runtime).
#
# Exception (Vercel CLI local case): an explicit local/test runtime always
# wins. The Vercel CLI may write VERCEL_ENV="preview" into your local
# .env.local while you run `next dev`. Because NODE_ENV is "development"
# (or "test" under vitest), that is treated as NON-real-data and dev headers
# keep working — the preview marker only counts on a deployed runtime.
#
# In a real-data environment the application FAILS CLOSED at startup (and the
# auth adapter selection refuses to run) unless ALL of the following hold:
#   - ENABLE_AUTHJS_REQUEST_CONTEXT="true"   (real Auth.js tenant adapter ON)
#   - ENABLE_DEV_AUTH_CONTEXT is unset/false (dev x-dev-* header bypass OFF)
#   - VITE_DEV_BUSINESS_ID is unset          (frontend dev override absent)
#
# Local development (next dev / NODE_ENV=development) is NOT a real-data
# environment, so the dev-header adapter and VITE_DEV_BUSINESS_ID keep
# working exactly as today. Set the dev flags in .env.local (git-ignored),
# never in committed config.
#
# Real-data example (uncomment in a real deployment):
# ENABLE_AUTHJS_REQUEST_CONTEXT="true"
#
# Local-dev example (put in .env.local, NOT here):
# ENABLE_DEV_AUTH_CONTEXT="true"
